  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>Standard DCF models have severe limitations when applied to Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs) like Prologis. This model penalizes the company for growth.</p>

  <h3>Why Standard DCF Misses The Mark on REITs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Standard FCF Subtracts Growth Capex:</strong> FCF is Operating Cash Flow minus Total Capital Expenditures. Prologis spent $3.67B on capex in 2025, but the vast majority of this was building new warehouses (growth), not maintaining existing ones. This artificially depresses FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>REITs Don't Retain Earnings:</strong> REITs are legally required to distribute 90% of taxable income as dividends. They cannot fund growth purely through retained earnings like a tech company. They must constantly issue debt and equity.</li>
    <li><strong>AFFO vs. FCF:</strong> Wall Street values REITs based on Adjusted Funds From Operations (AFFO) or Net Asset Value (NAV), not standard free cash flow. AFFO only subtracts maintenance capex, providing a much higher baseline cash generation metric.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt is Natural:</strong> The model subtracts $35B in debt to arrive at Equity Value. While mathematically correct for EV, REITs comfortably carry high debt levels collateralized by hard real estate assets.</li>
  </ul>

